'Orbment' is a general term for devices that operate

The internal structure of an orbment allows it to

While quartz are both an energy source and capable

Blade II is a card game in which two players
take turns placing numbered cards on
the field and vie for the greater sum total.
Once both players have been dealt their
hands, they must each draw a card from
the deck and place it on the field.
The player who draws the lower number
must then proceed to place a card from
The player who goes second must then
play a card with a value that allows them
to surpass their opponent's current total.
This process repeats until one player can
no longer surpass their opponent's total
value, or they run out of cards.
Should both players have an equal total
at any point, the field is cleared and both
players must draw and play new cards.
If the final card of the game is used to clear
the field, the match will result in a draw.
There are five types of cards in Blade.
Blade Cards are the most common. They are
Bolt Cards remove the last card that your
As a special rule, a Blade Card with a
value of 1 can be used to bring back a
card removed by the use of a Bolt Card.
Mirror Cards are used to switch the
positions of the cards currently placed
Blast Cards allow you to choose one of
your opponent's cards to discard. This does
not let you see their hand, however.
Force Cards double your current total.
These are very powerful cards, but require
careful usage to achieve their full effect.
Bolt, Mirror, Blast, and Force Cards each
have a value of 1 if they are the first card
to be placed on the field.
